Oof those first few runs back. I am a huge fan of taking down time after your last big race of the season. It’s so needed to mentally and physically refresh.

That means you will lose some fitness, but that’s not a bad thing. In order to build back stronger and faster than before your body needs that recover time. 

The hardest part I find for a lot of athletes is letting go of to the paces or the distances they usually go. After a few weeks off things will be moving a little slower as you get back and forcing that speed or volume is a sure way to head towards injury. 

So to get back into running after taking down time build back slowly, use HR or perceived exertion instead of pace so you are training the correct zones and not forcing the speed. It’s always safer to do shorter more frequent runs to build up volume so you are less impeded by fatigue and running more with good form. With lower volume this is a great time to incorporate that mobility or strength work you had been skipping because of fatigue or lack of time just trying to get the miles jn 😉

If you are looking for some mobility or strength work to stay injury free check out @endurancefitapp and try some of the free workouts!

While not perfect here are some tips improve your FTP - check out the link to my latest blog for more info and an FTP building workout. 

There is no one best way but a combination of factors in addition to structured training sessions, that can help you increase your threshold Watts:

Build a strong aerobic base: FTP is largely determined by your aerobic energy system, so it’s important to focus on building a strong aerobic base. This can be achieved through steady-state rides at an easy to moderate intensity, as well as incorporating low-intensity endurance rides into your training plan.
Incorporate strength training: In addition to cycling-specific workouts, adding strength training to your training plan can help improve your FTP. Strength training helps to increase muscle mass and power, which can translate to improved cycling performance.
Don’t forget to recover: It’s important to give your body time to recover from hard workouts. Make sure to include rest days and active recovery days in your training plan, and be sure to get enough sleep and nourishment to support your training.
Test and track your FTP: Regularly testing and tracking your FTP can help you monitor your progress and set training goals. You can do an FTP test using a ramp test or a time trial, and track it using a power meter or training software.
By incorporating FTP-boosting workouts, building a strong aerobic base, adding strength training, and properly recovering, you can effectively increase your FTP and improve your cycling performance. Happy cycling!

Coach’s Tip: One of my favorite ways to level up an athletes run is a long run with a fast finish. 

Not only will this workout give your legs a good burn, but it will also challenge you mentally and set you up to deal with the mental and physical challenges of the last few miles of your race. 

Read the full article with a workout on my website - link in my bio 

But why is a long run with a fast finish so beneficial for training? For starters, it helps improve your endurance and cardiovascular fitness. By running at a Z2 effort or steady pace for a longer distance, you are giving your body the opportunity to adapt and become more efficient at using oxygen, which can help increase your overall endurance when putting in the miles.

Additionally, the fast finish portion of the workout will help you build speed and power. This is because when you push yourself to run faster at the end of a long run, you are recruiting more muscle fibers and increasing the intensity of the workout. This can lead to improvements in your overall speed and power so you can hit your goal time.

But still one of the great benefits of a long run with a fast finish is that it simulates the feeling you experience at the end of a race. When you’re nearing the finish line, your muscles are likely fatigued and you may feel like you’ve hit a wall. But, in order to cross that finish line, you need to dig deep and push through the discomfort.

I’ve been in a writing mood lately and always love to chat triathlon. New article up with some Top Tips to Crush your Triathlon goals.

Training for your first Ironman or Chasing a New PR or World Champs Qualification can seem daunting, but with the right approach, it can also be a rewarding and life-changing experience. There is nothing like crossing that finish line during a successful Ironman and hearing, “You are an Ironman”

Here are some tips to help you prepare for your Ironman race and cross the finish line with confidence. 

Click through to the article in my bio for more details on each tip:

1) Gradual Increase in Volume: The biggest pitfall I see with athletes is being excited and motivated to jump right in and crush some epic workouts. That leaves them exhaused and cooked so they need 3-4 days of recovery. Overall you will gain fitness quicker be better off with consistent training and recovery so you can keep training consistently than big crazy training days.

2) Strength Training: Strength training is an important component of Ironman training. Building muscular endurance can improve your performance and help you tackle the physical demands of the race.

3) Testing Your Nutrition and Fueling: Proper nutrition and fueling are crucial for a successful Ironman race, and it’s important to test out your strategy in training. This will help you determine what works best for your body and avoid any surprises on race day.

Attention Ironman Calgary 70.3 racers! Wondering about the new course? Well, I did a recon for you, and here’s the course lowdown!

1️⃣ Some worries about gravel on the road but they will be cleaning the gravelly bits before race day.

2️⃣ There’s a 2-meter gravel stretch, but fear not - race organizers are on it.

3️⃣ The GPS file shows a route down a road that turns to gravel, but I talked to the race org and the turnaround is well before the tarmac ends.

4️⃣ There are rumble strips before a stop sign - no worries, just check your bottles are snug and secure.

5️⃣ The first turnaround is like a fun lollipop! You can keep your speed up and skip the tricky 180° turn.

6️⃣ Wind factor? I rode two days: calm and windy. Without wind, the first half is slower, and it picks up in the second. Add wind, and it’s the other way around. So, ride to your power or perceived effort - wind affects everyone equally.

The course? Love it! Less elevation than last year with only one significant climb. Key takeaways: secure those bottles, pace your effort, and above all - savor the thrill of race day!

Yesterday I quit half way through a bicycle race. 

The legs were there, I was able to go with all of the attacks and the big hill that felt brutal last year even on the first lap was just a strong effort to get up. 

So why did I quit? I just really didn’t want to be there. 

Now maybe that sounds soft in this “No Pain, No Gain” mentality that is all over social media. 

For me, I love endurance sports. I love seeing what my body is capable of and pushing through perceived limits. 

For me to really not want to be there, when the body is feeling good and the power is coming is a big red flag. 

The ONLY reason for me to keep pushing when I felt like that would be because of other people’s perception or expectations of me. It’s embarrassing to pull out, when I talked about the races and put myself out there. 

But that’s not a good enough reason, though it would have kept me in the race years ago out of insecurity. 

Lots of reasons why I just wasn’t in the right headspace for it, but those are mine to deal with. 

I had a great talk with my coach @runnerlucho that put me in a good headspace and he knows me well after 10 years. He said to just go run today, ignore the data and do what feels good. That’s my happy place, when I can just quiet my head and do what I love. 

So 18 miles later I was sore and achy and grinning from ear to ear. One of those runs where I just cruised, fell into that flow state and followed my feet. 

I’ll probably go try the Crit tomorrow. It’s going to feel terrible with an 18 mile run in the legs, but that’s ok. 

It’s been years since I’ve finished a race not on the podium, never mind not making it to the finish line. I just need to take a step back let go of any expectations. What can I say, I’m human 🤷‍♀️

Ok ladies, and men who coach women, let’s talk about hormones. 

This was after one of those runs where it just felt like flying even though I had put in a massive bike ride the day before. 

Understanding how hormones ebb and flow through the menstrual cycle is crucial to maximizing athletic performance. Trust me, I’ve been there!

In the first half of your cycle (Follicular Phase), estrogen and testosterone are your BFFs, often leading to better muscle endurance and recovery. Body temperature is lower, you are stronger and more explosive. The second half (Luteal Phase) can be trickier. You might experience fatigue, bloating, higher body temperature or just not feeling like your usual self due to elevated progesterone.

Case in point: Last week, I had a 2-3 hour ride on Zwift, aiming for multiple laps up the Epic KOM. I was grinding away in Zone 3 with 50-70 rpm, and guess what? I managed only three climbs and had to cut my ride short at 2.5 hours just exhausted. This was just a couple of days before my cycle started.

Fast forward to a few days later, post-cycle, I tackled the same Epic KOM climb, this time with even more tired legs. The result? FIVE reps up the climb during a 5-hour ride, with higher power, and it felt exhilarating rather than exhausting. Followed by one of my best runs the next day because my body could recover from the effort. 

Trust me, your hormones are powerful performance modulators. Understanding them can literally elevate your game. Not only taking advantage of when you are primed to performs physically, BUT also understanding why some days you just don’t have it even though you’ve been able to do a workout in the past. It’s not that you’re being weak or not mentally tough enough.

Has life ever gotten in the way of your training? Missed a crucial training session and panicking? 🏊‍♂️🚴‍♀️🏃‍♂️ 

You’re not alone. When that occurs, the question that looms in the minds of many athletes is, “Should I make up for the missed session?” The answer isn’t a simple yes or no; it varies depending on the type of training session missed.

Here are some quick tips but click the link in my bio for the full article. 

Missing a Recovery Session

Should You Make Up for It?

No. Recovery sessions are designed to give your body a break. Missing one isn’t the end of the world.

Missing a Long Endurance Session

Should You Make Up for It?

Possibly, but it’s crucial to avoid back-to-back long sessions as it increases injury risk. If you can’t get in a full long session getting in what you can is still beneficial.

Missing a Key Race Pace Session

Should You Make Up for It?

Yes, but with caveats. Race pace sessions are essential for goal setting and mental preparation. However they are often big sessions and they need to have recovery before and after them so make sure to plan it where you can get that recovery time. 

General Guidelines for Any Missed Session

Don’t Panic: Missing a single session will not ruin your overall performance. Training is about the cumulative effect over months of consistency and triaining.

Adjust the Plan, but Don’t Overcompensate: It’s tempting to go all out to ‘make up’ for the lost time. This usually leads to overtraining and burnout.

Consult Your Coach: If you have a coach, consult with them to adjust your training schedule smartly.

Remember, training is not just about physical strength but also about adaptability and resilience. Sometimes missing a session can be a blessing in disguise, offering you an unexpected yet needed rest day. Always listen to your body and adjust your training plan as needed.

Have you ever gained weight during a Triathlon or Marathon build up? Read below to see why and how to avoid it. 

💥Triathlon coaching spot available DM for details💥 

There are a few reasons you could be gaining weight during endurance training, and it’s not uncommon. I’m usually the leanest I am early season and then as I get closer to race day even I add on a few extra lbs. 

I’m going to dive into the one often overlooked - The hormone Cortisol

1) A small increase in cortisol is a good thing, it helps you crush workouts and stay focussed. However if you continue to push your body with a tough training schedule and without proper recovery, cortisol increases and works against you. 

Cortisol has a relationship with the hormone insulin, which controls blood sugar. When cortisol levels increase, our body can become resistant to insulin. In turn, this may lead to an increase in blood sugar, weight gain, food cravings and disrupted sleep. 

Bottom line if your cortisol is too high from lack of recovery you are sleeping less, eating/craving more junk food and likely gaining weight as your body is under stress. 

2) Rewarding hard/long workouts with treats or huge meals - the ‘I earned this’ mentality. Treating yourself when you are active and working hard is not a bad thing, I’m all about balance (and chocolate intake) just don’t make it after EVERY workout. 

3) Using calories to try to overcome fatigue - I’m guilty of this one 😊I’m tired I must need more carbs for this workout when in reality I’m just tired and all the carbs in the world won’t change that. 

4) DOMS -after particularity hard workouts in the short term your weight will go up as your muscles become swollen with fluid as they try to repair. This can also be true the first 2 weeks of a new workout program. 

5) Muscle gain - ok a lot of us will believe this is the reason we are gaining weight or justify it. Yes there is some muscle gain with endurance training but if your scale has gone up 10lbs it’s unlikely it’s all muscle mass.

So in today’s episode of ‘I’m human’, I did a VO2 max test... and only made it 95% of the way through. 

11 years in the sport and this was my first time doing lab testing. Ironman has been the focus since I started and with that as long as your zones are close enough, that’s good enough there is so much else that goes into a great race day. 

But next year I’m switching to short and fast stuff and at the moment the speeds I need to be competitive on the run are far beyond my current capability. So I went to @tcrsportlab to see where I am at and do some testing to dial in zones. 

What I didn’t predict was how anxiety inducing the mask for the v02 max test would be😜 The mask in combination with just going harder and breathing heavier than I ever do had my panicking a bit and jumping off before reaching max HR. Hopefully next time will go better just having experienced it once before. 

But hey, every experience is a learning opportunity, right? Here’s what I discovered from this test:

1. I’m an exceptionally efficient fat burner, at 157bpm I’m still 50/50 carbs to fat burning. No surprise after a decade-long focus on endurance. However, as the intensity ramps up, there’s a drastic shift from fat to sugar burning very quickly. 

2. This dramatic shift shows that while I’ve built a strong base, there’s a whole realm of high-intensity performance I haven’t tapped into yet.

3. Knowing my aerobic ceiling and how my body switches from fat to sugar burning at higher intensities allows for more specific training zones. This means I can train more effectively, targeting the exact areas I need to improve for faster, explosive racing.

4. A Whole New World of Speed. After 11 years focusing on endurance, this shift excites me. It means there’s so much trainable, untapped potential waiting to be unleashed. It’s not just about getting faster; it’s about evolving as an athlete.

Every test tells a story. Now I’m ready to dive into this new chapter. Shorter, faster, stronger-let’s do this.

As I coach I’ve seen athletes struggle with this over the years…

The #1 mistake - trying to hack the system and over complicating it all. 

Triathlon is all about consistency putting in the work and supporting that ability to continue to put in the work with adequate recovery. 

Or if you want some guidance reach out to learn more about coaching and how I can take the mental energy out of training so you can focus on getting it done. 

Here’s what you need to focus on:

🔑 Consistency Over Intensity: Regular, moderate training beats sporadic, intense sessions. If you do a super hero session and feel terrible for the next week you are not making progress. 

🧠 Smart Goal Setting: Set specific, measurable, and realistic goals. Whether it’s shaving off minutes from your swim or mastering your bike technique, clear targets guide your training and focus.

🍽️ Nutrition as Your Fuel: Eating right isn’t just about race day. It’s about properly fueling your body throughout your training cycle. Whether body composition is one of your goals or not you need fuel to gain fitness and support your hormonal health. 

🛌 Recovery is Crucial: Incorporate rest days and recovery techniques into your routine. All of the hacks and supplements in the world aren’t as good as consistent quality sleep.
